reviewText: This was actually released in 1968 and directed by Alfonso Brescia. It isn't an American film and the audio is dubbed. Considering both the storyline and the timeline, it becomes a more interesting film. Films of this genre are usually difficult to find, are in another language or have subtitles. Knowing this information beforehand gives one a better perspective. If you enjoy the vintage WWII movies, it becomes an interesting commentary on European films and producers. The quality of the footage is grainy and slightly blurred and the audio is dated. Recommended for those interested in this genre and for those who are interested in learning. Read the reviews . . . it is simply a matter of preference.

reviewText: The production in this film is very rough. The acting was marginal. It is historically very inaccurate--the planes carrying the paratroopers on D-Day never took off for a June 5th landing. The decision to delay was made early enough in the day that plenty of notice was given to the paratroop units that the landing was delayed. The only reason I watched it through is that it is a WWII movie, and I watch 'em all.
Title: Hell in Normandy

reviewText: A third tier film, but not without interest. Italian companies apparently made several of these and none are outstanding although they can be diverting.
summary: Less than a B film but OK
Title: Hell in Normandy

reviewText: For fans of Euro-war movies this is a must have. It's not accurate(the American GI's wear Italian camo) but it is entertaining. Never let facts get in the way of a good story. The DVD itself is good quality even though it's a play only disc with no extra's or scene selection. These movies are hard to find, so, you have to tolerate some loss of picture quality.
Title: Hell in Normandy
